('additional-maths:2-2-the-factor-theorem-and-cubics:misc:4ec5ab0f', 'additional-maths', 'additional-maths:2-2-the-factor-theorem-and-cubics', '2.2 The Factor Theorem and Cubics', 'misc', 'mcq', 1, '{"readingTitle": "Misconception check", "reading": "<p><strong>❌ Common misconception:</strong> On a ''detailed reasoning'' question, quoting the three factors straight from a calculator.</p><p><strong>✅ The correct idea:</strong> DR needs the method seen: show \\( \\text{f}(a)=0 \\) and obtain the quadratic factor. A weak answer gives factors only (0 marks); a strong answer shows every step.</p>", "question": "A DR factor-theorem answer with no working scores:", "options": ["full marks", "zero", "one mark", "half marks"]}'::jsonb, '{"answer": 1, "explain": "Answer-only DR responses score zero, even when the factorisation is correct."}'::jsonb),
('additional-maths:2-2-the-factor-theorem-and-cubics:misc:7630575e', 'additional-maths', 'additional-maths:2-2-the-factor-theorem-and-cubics', '2.2 The Factor Theorem and Cubics', 'misc', 'mcq', 1, '{"readingTitle": "Misconception check", "reading": "<p><strong>❌ Common misconception:</strong> Using successive factor-theorem trials and stopping at the first factor found, \\( x = -1 \\).</p><p><strong>✅ The correct idea:</strong> A cubic has three roots. After one factor, find the quadratic factor to catch the rest — including a REPEATED root. For \\( x^3-3x-2 \\), stopping at \\( x=-1 \\) misses that it is repeated.</p>", "question": "\\( x^3 - 3x - 2 = 0 \\) has root \\( x = 2 \\). The other root(s):", "options": ["\\( x = -1 \\) (repeated)", "\\( x = -1 \\) only, ignore repeats", "\\( x = 1 \\)", "there are none"]}'::jsonb, '{"answer": 0, "explain": "\\( x^3-3x-2=(x-2)(x+1)^2 \\), so \\( x=-1 \\) is a repeated root."}'::jsonb),
('additional-maths:2-2-the-factor-theorem-and-cubics:misc:a5227c8d', 'additional-maths', 'additional-maths:2-2-the-factor-theorem-and-cubics', '2.2 The Factor Theorem and Cubics', 'misc', 'mcq', 1, '{"readingTitle": "Misconception check", "reading": "<p><strong>❌ Common misconception:</strong> For a cubic with constant term 6, testing only \\( x = 1 \\) and \\( x = 2 \\).</p><p><strong>✅ The correct idea:</strong> The whole-number candidates are ALL divisors of the constant term: \\( \\pm1, \\pm2, \\pm3, \\pm6 \\) (plus fractions like \\( \\pm\\tfrac{1}{2}, \\pm\\tfrac{3}{2} \\) if the leading coefficient is not 1).</p>", "question": "For a cubic with constant term 6, test:", "options": ["\\( \\pm1, \\pm2, \\pm3, \\pm6 \\)", "\\( 1 \\) and \\( 2 \\) only", "even numbers only", "\\( \\pm6 \\) only"]}'::jsonb, '{"answer": 0, "explain": "All divisors of the constant term are candidates: \\( \\pm1, \\pm2, \\pm3, \\pm6 \\)."}'::jsonb),
('additional-maths:2-2-the-factor-theorem-and-cubics:tips:c667f48c', 'additional-maths', 'additional-maths:2-2-the-factor-theorem-and-cubics', '2.2 The Factor Theorem and Cubics', 'tips', 'mcq', 1, '{"readingTitle": "explain — The ''detailed reasoning'' ladder", "reading": "<p><strong>0 marks:</strong> writing \\( \\text{f}(x) = (x+1)(x-2)(x-4) \\) straight from the calculator with no working — even though it is correct.</p><p><strong>Partial:</strong> showing \\( \\text{f}(2) = 0 \\) (so \\( (x-2) \\) is a factor) but then jumping to the three factors.</p><p><strong>Full marks:</strong> show \\( \\text{f}(2) = 0 \\), obtain the quadratic factor \\( (x^2 - 3x - 4) \\), factorise it, then state \\( (x-2)(x-4)(x+1) \\).</p>", "question": "On a DR factor question, the safest response:", "options": ["show \\( \\text{f}(a)=0 \\) then find the quadratic factor", "write the three factors straight from the calculator display", "give decimals", "state the remainder"]}'::jsonb, '{"answer": 0, "explain": "DR rewards the full visible method: \\( \\text{f}(a)=0 \\) then the quadratic factor."}'::jsonb),
('additional-maths:2-2-the-factor-theorem-and-cubics:tips:90cae5f1', 'additional-maths', 'additional-maths:2-2-the-factor-theorem-and-cubics', '2.2 The Factor Theorem and Cubics', 'tips', 'mcq', 1, '{"readingTitle": "tip — The sign trap: (x − a) matches f(a)", "reading": "<p>The number you substitute is the <strong>opposite sign</strong> to the one in the bracket. To test \\( (x + 5) \\), evaluate \\( \\text{f}(-5) \\); to test \\( (x - 5) \\), evaluate \\( \\text{f}(5) \\). Getting this backwards is the most common way to miss a factor entirely.</p>", "question": "To check \\( (x + 5) \\) is a factor, evaluate:", "options": ["\\( \\text{f}(5) \\)", "\\( \\text{f}(-5) \\)", "\\( \\text{f}(0) \\)", "\\( \\text{f}(\\tfrac{1}{5}) \\)"]}'::jsonb, '{"answer": 1, "explain": "\\( (x+5)=(x-(-5)) \\), so evaluate \\( \\text{f}(-5) \\)."}'::jsonb),
('additional-maths:2-2-the-factor-theorem-and-cubics:tips:5556e4bc', 'additional-maths', 'additional-maths:2-2-the-factor-theorem-and-cubics', '2.2 The Factor Theorem and Cubics', 'tips', 'mcq', 1, '{"readingTitle": "explain — Factorising is not solving", "reading": "<p>If the command word is <strong>\"solve\"</strong>, the factorisation is only the halfway point. \\( (x-1)(2x-3)(x+2) \\) earns the factorising marks, but the final answer marks need the roots: set each factor to zero and write \\( x = 1,\\ \\tfrac{3}{2},\\ -2 \\). Don''t leave marks on the table by stopping early.</p>", "question": "You have factorised \\( \\text{f}(x) \\). To finish ''solve \\( \\text{f}(x)=0 \\)'':", "options": ["set each factor equal to zero", "stop — the factorised form is already the solution", "expand the brackets again", "find \\( \\text{f}(0) \\)"]}'::jsonb, '{"answer": 0, "explain": "Solving means setting every factor to zero to read off the roots."}'::jsonb),
