('additional-maths:2-3-setting-up-and-solving-equations:mcq:f628458a', 'additional-maths', 'additional-maths:2-3-setting-up-and-solving-equations', '2.3 Setting Up and Solving Equations', 'mcq', 'mcq', 1, '{"question": "The product of three consecutive positive integers is 60. The smallest integer is:", "options": ["3", "4", "5", "2"]}'::jsonb, '{"answer": 0, "explain": "\\( n(n+1)(n+2) = 60 \\); \\( 3 \\times 4 \\times 5 = 60 \\), so the smallest is 3."}'::jsonb),
('additional-maths:2-3-setting-up-and-solving-equations:tf:354ba72a', 'additional-maths', 'additional-maths:2-3-setting-up-and-solving-equations', '2.3 Setting Up and Solving Equations', 'tf', 'tf', 1, '{"question": "When setting up an equation you should state what your variable represents, including its units."}'::jsonb, '{"answer": true, "explain": "Defining the unknown (with units) is step 1 and prevents lost marks later."}'::jsonb),
('additional-maths:2-3-setting-up-and-solving-equations:tf:83d2b412', 'additional-maths', 'additional-maths:2-3-setting-up-and-solving-equations', '2.3 Setting Up and Solving Equations', 'tf', 'tf', 1, '{"question": "A negative solution to an equation for a length should still be given as a valid answer."}'::jsonb, '{"answer": false, "explain": "A length cannot be negative, so a negative root is inadmissible and must be rejected."}'::jsonb),
('additional-maths:2-3-setting-up-and-solving-equations:tf:6f71555a', 'additional-maths', 'additional-maths:2-3-setting-up-and-solving-equations', '2.3 Setting Up and Solving Equations', 'tf', 'tf', 1, '{"question": "\"8 more than a number \\( x \\)\" is written \\( 8x \\)."}'::jsonb, '{"answer": false, "explain": "''8 more than'' adds 8: it is \\( x + 8 \\), not \\( 8x \\) (that would be ''8 times'')."}'::jsonb),
('additional-maths:2-3-setting-up-and-solving-equations:tf:752b457b', 'additional-maths', 'additional-maths:2-3-setting-up-and-solving-equations', '2.3 Setting Up and Solving Equations', 'tf', 'tf', 1, '{"question": "To solve a linear equation and a quadratic equation together, you substitute the linear equation into the quadratic."}'::jsonb, '{"answer": true, "explain": "Substitution reduces the pair to a single quadratic in one variable."}'::jsonb),
('additional-maths:2-3-setting-up-and-solving-equations:tf:83676af1', 'additional-maths', 'additional-maths:2-3-setting-up-and-solving-equations', '2.3 Setting Up and Solving Equations', 'tf', 'tf', 1, '{"question": "A quadratic set up from a context always has two admissible solutions."}'::jsonb, '{"answer": false, "explain": "Often one root (or both) is inadmissible — e.g. negative — and must be rejected."}'::jsonb),
('additional-maths:2-3-setting-up-and-solving-equations:tf:33aab511', 'additional-maths', 'additional-maths:2-3-setting-up-and-solving-equations', '2.3 Setting Up and Solving Equations', 'tf', 'tf', 1, '{"question": "For the 2023 boat problem, giving the answer as \"\\( r = 1 \\)\" with no units earns full marks."}'::jsonb, '{"answer": false, "explain": "The final mark needed the value in context with units: ''speed of the current = 1 km/h''."}'::jsonb),
('additional-maths:2-3-setting-up-and-solving-equations:tf:f8337d3c', 'additional-maths', 'additional-maths:2-3-setting-up-and-solving-equations', '2.3 Setting Up and Solving Equations', 'tf', 'tf', 1, '{"question": "The product of three consecutive integers \\( n,\\ n+1,\\ n+2 \\) can be written \\( n^3 + 3n^2 + 2n \\)."}'::jsonb, '{"answer": true, "explain": "\\( n(n+1)(n+2) = n(n^2 + 3n + 2) = n^3 + 3n^2 + 2n \\)."}'::jsonb),
('additional-maths:2-3-setting-up-and-solving-equations:tf:76230e7a', 'additional-maths', 'additional-maths:2-3-setting-up-and-solving-equations', '2.3 Setting Up and Solving Equations', 'tf', 'tf', 1, '{"question": "If substituting a line into a circle gives a quadratic with no real roots, the line misses the circle."}'::jsonb, '{"answer": true, "explain": "No real solutions means no intersection points — the line does not meet the circle."}'::jsonb),
('additional-maths:2-3-setting-up-and-solving-equations:learn:efd605a1', 'additional-maths', 'additional-maths:2-3-setting-up-and-solving-equations', '2.3 Setting Up and Solving Equations', 'learn', 'mcq', 1, '{"readingTitle": "How do you turn a worded problem into an equation?", "reading": "<p><strong>Setting up an equation</strong> means translating a real situation into algebra you can solve. The same five-step routine works whether the equation turns out to be linear, quadratic or cubic.</p>\n            <table class=\"worked\">\n              <tr><td>1. <strong>Define the unknown.</strong> Write \"Let \\( x \\) be …\" and include its <strong>units</strong> (cm, km/h, £).</td></tr>\n              <tr><td>2. <strong>Translate</strong> each sentence into algebra — \"5 more than\" is \\( +5 \\), \"3 times\" is \\( 3x \\), \"product\" is a multiplication.</td></tr>\n              <tr><td>3. <strong>Solve</strong> the equation using the right method for its degree.</td></tr>\n              <tr><td>4. <strong>Interpret</strong> the solution back in the context, with units.</td></tr>\n              <tr><td>5. <strong>Reject</strong> any solution that cannot occur (a negative length, a fractional number of people).</td></tr>\n            </table>\n            <p>The commonest lost marks are skipping step 1 (never saying what \\( x \\) is) and skipping steps 4–5 (leaving a bare number instead of a value in context).</p>", "question": "What should the very first line of a set-up-a-model answer do?", "options": ["Define the unknown and state its units", "Write down the final answer", "Draw a graph", "Multiply out every bracket before doing anything else"]}'::jsonb, '{"answer": 0, "explain": "Always define your variable first — it makes every later step (and every mark) unambiguous."}'::jsonb),
('additional-maths:2-3-setting-up-and-solving-equations:learn:c77db955', 'additional-maths', 'additional-maths:2-3-setting-up-and-solving-equations', '2.3 Setting Up and Solving Equations', 'learn', 'mcq', 1, '{"readingTitle": "How do you set up and solve a linear equation in context?", "reading": "<p>A <strong>linear equation</strong> has the unknown only to the power 1. Translate the words, then rearrange.</p>\n            <p><strong>Worked example.</strong> A taxi charges a £3 booking fee plus £2 for every mile. A journey costs £17. How many miles was it?</p>\n            <table class=\"worked\">\n              <tr><td>1. Let \\( m \\) be the number of miles.</td></tr>\n              <tr><td>2. Cost = fee + rate × miles: \\( 3 + 2m = 17 \\).</td></tr>\n              <tr><td>3. Subtract 3: \\( 2m = 14 \\); divide by 2: \\( m = 7 \\).</td></tr>\n              <tr><td>4. In context: the journey was <strong>7 miles</strong>.</td></tr>\n            </table>\n            <p>Check: \\( 3 + 2(7) = 17 \\). ✓ Notice the answer is a <em>value with units</em>, not just \"7\".</p>", "question": "A plumber charges £40 plus £30 per hour. A bill is £160. Which equation finds the hours \\( h \\)?", "options": ["\\( 40 + 30h = 160 \\)", "\\( 40h + 30 = 160 \\)", "\\( 70h = 160 \\)", "\\( 40 + 30 + h = 160 \\)"]}'::jsonb, '{"answer": 0, "explain": "Fixed £40 plus £30 for each hour: \\( 40 + 30h = 160 \\), giving \\( h = 4 \\) hours."}'::jsonb),
('additional-maths:2-3-setting-up-and-solving-equations:learn:c4fe7ac8', 'additional-maths', 'additional-maths:2-3-setting-up-and-solving-equations', '2.3 Setting Up and Solving Equations', 'learn', 'mcq', 1, '{"readingTitle": "How do you set up and solve a quadratic in context?", "reading": "<p>When two quantities <strong>multiply</strong> (an area, a product of numbers), the equation is usually a <strong>quadratic</strong>. Rearrange to \\( ax^2 + bx + c = 0 \\), solve, then keep only the physically valid root.</p>\n            <p><strong>Worked example.</strong> A rectangle is 2 cm longer than it is wide. Its area is 48 cm². Find its dimensions.</p>\n            <table class=\"worked\">\n              <tr><td>1. Let the width be \\( x \\) cm; the length is \\( (x + 2) \\) cm.</td></tr>\n              <tr><td>2. Area: \\( x(x + 2) = 48 \\).</td></tr>\n              <tr><td>3. Expand and rearrange: \\( x^2 + 2x - 48 = 0 \\).</td></tr>\n              <tr><td>4. Factorise: \\( (x + 8)(x - 6) = 0 \\), so \\( x = -8 \\) or \\( x = 6 \\).</td></tr>\n              <tr><td>5. A width cannot be negative, so <strong>reject \\( x = -8 \\)</strong>.</td></tr>\n            </table>\n            <p>So the width is <strong>6 cm</strong> and the length is <strong>8 cm</strong>. Check: \\( 6 \\times 8 = 48 \\). ✓ Stating why you reject \\( x = -8 \\) is part of the answer.</p>", "question": "A quadratic modelling a length gives roots \\( x = 5 \\) and \\( x = -9 \\). The length is:", "options": ["\\( 5 \\) (reject \\( -9 \\): a length can''t be negative)", "\\( -9 \\)", "\\( 5 \\) or \\( -9 \\), since both values satisfy the equation", "\\( -4 \\), the sum of the roots"]}'::jsonb, '{"answer": 0, "explain": "Only the positive root is admissible for a length; you must reject \\( -9 \\) and say why."}'::jsonb),
('additional-maths:2-3-setting-up-and-solving-equations:learn:b4bec774', 'additional-maths', 'additional-maths:2-3-setting-up-and-solving-equations', '2.3 Setting Up and Solving Equations', 'learn', 'mcq', 1, '{"readingTitle": "How do you set up and solve a cubic in context?", "reading": "<p>When <strong>three</strong> quantities multiply (a volume, three consecutive numbers), you get a <strong>cubic</strong>. Find one root by inspection or the <strong>factor theorem</strong> (topic 2.2), then factor out to a quadratic and finish.</p>\n            <p><strong>Worked example.</strong> Three consecutive positive integers have a product of 60. Find them.</p>\n            <table class=\"worked\">\n              <tr><td>1. Let the smallest be \\( n \\); the integers are \\( n,\\ n+1,\\ n+2 \\).</td></tr>\n              <tr><td>2. Product: \\( n(n+1)(n+2) = 60 \\), i.e. \\( n^3 + 3n^2 + 2n - 60 = 0 \\).</td></tr>\n              <tr><td>3. Try \\( n = 3 \\): \\( 3 \\times 4 \\times 5 = 60 \\) ✓, so \\( (n - 3) \\) is a factor.</td></tr>\n              <tr><td>4. Divide out: \\( (n - 3)(n^2 + 6n + 20) = 0 \\).</td></tr>\n              <tr><td>5. The factor \\( n^2 + 6n + 20 \\) has discriminant \\( 36 - 80 < 0 \\) — no real roots.</td></tr>\n            </table>\n            <p>So \\( n = 3 \\), and the integers are <strong>3, 4 and 5</strong>. The quadratic factor is checked, not ignored — showing it has no valid roots is what confirms \\( n = 3 \\) is the only answer.</p>", "question": "After spotting \\( n = 3 \\) is a root of a cubic, the next step is to:", "options": ["Factor out \\( (n - 3) \\) to get a quadratic, then solve that", "Stop, because finding one root already answers the whole question", "Square both sides", "Reject \\( n = 3 \\)"]}'::jsonb, '{"answer": 0, "explain": "Dividing out the known factor leaves a quadratic that reveals (or rules out) the remaining roots."}'::jsonb),
('additional-maths:2-3-setting-up-and-solving-equations:learn:cabb36f3', 'additional-maths', 'additional-maths:2-3-setting-up-and-solving-equations', '2.3 Setting Up and Solving Equations', 'learn', 'mcq', 1, '{"readingTitle": "How do you solve linear–quadratic simultaneous equations?", "reading": "<p>To solve a <strong>linear</strong> equation and a <strong>non-linear</strong> one together (a line meeting a curve), use <strong>substitution</strong>: rearrange the linear equation for one variable and put it into the other.</p>\n            <p><strong>Worked example.</strong> Solve \\( y = x + 1 \\) and \\( x^2 + y^2 = 25 \\) simultaneously.</p>\n            <table class=\"worked\">\n              <tr><td>1. Substitute \\( y = x + 1 \\) into the second equation: \\( x^2 + (x + 1)^2 = 25 \\).</td></tr>\n              <tr><td>2. Expand: \\( x^2 + x^2 + 2x + 1 = 25 \\), so \\( 2x^2 + 2x - 24 = 0 \\).</td></tr>\n              <tr><td>3. Divide by 2 and factorise: \\( x^2 + x - 12 = 0 = (x + 4)(x - 3) \\).</td></tr>\n              <tr><td>4. So \\( x = -4 \\) or \\( x = 3 \\).</td></tr>\n              <tr><td>5. Back-substitute into \\( y = x + 1 \\): \\( (3,\\ 4) \\) and \\( (-4,\\ -3) \\).</td></tr>\n            </table>\n            <p>Always give the answers as <strong>pairs</strong> — each \\( x \\) with its matching \\( y \\). Check \\( 3^2 + 4^2 = 25 \\) ✓ and \\( (-4)^2 + (-3)^2 = 25 \\) ✓.</p>", "question": "To solve \\( y = 2x \\) and \\( x^2 + y^2 = 20 \\), the substitution gives:", "options": ["\\( x^2 + (2x)^2 = 20 \\)", "\\( x^2 + 2x = 20 \\)", "\\( (2x)^2 = 20 \\)", "\\( x^2 + 2x^2 = 20 \\), so \\( 3x^2 = 20 \\)"]}'::jsonb, '{"answer": 0, "explain": "Replace \\( y \\) with \\( 2x \\): \\( x^2 + (2x)^2 = 20 \\Rightarrow 5x^2 = 20 \\Rightarrow x = \\pm 2 \\)."}'::jsonb),
('additional-maths:2-3-setting-up-and-solving-equations:learn:70690833', 'additional-maths', 'additional-maths:2-3-setting-up-and-solving-equations', '2.3 Setting Up and Solving Equations', 'learn', 'mcq', 1, '{"readingTitle": "Why must you interpret the answer and reject invalid solutions?", "reading": "<p>Solving the equation is only part of the mark. Modelling questions reward <strong>interpretation</strong>: turning \\( x = 6 \\) into \"the width is 6 cm\", and discarding anything impossible.</p>\n            <ul>\n              <li><strong>Reject inadmissible roots.</strong> Negative lengths, negative speeds, and fractional counts of people cannot occur — say which root you keep and <em>why</em>.</li>\n              <li><strong>State a value with its units.</strong> A bare number often loses the final mark: in the 2023 boat question, \"\\( r = 1 \\)\" scored nothing extra — the examiners wanted \"speed of the current = 1 km/h\".</li>\n              <li><strong>Watch what the variable stands for.</strong> If \\( r \\) was defined as a unitless number, \"\\( r = 1 \\) km/h\" is also wrong — name the quantity: \"the speed is 1 km/h\".</li>\n              <li><strong>\"Show that\" needs the last line.</strong> If a question asks you to show an equation simplifies to a printed result, you must reach that exact result on the page.</li>\n            </ul>\n            <p>Read the final sentence of the question back to yourself: does your answer actually name the thing it asked for, in the right units?</p>", "question": "A question asks for a swimmer''s speed and you find \\( v = 2 \\). The best final answer is:", "options": ["The speed is 2 m/s", "\\( v = 2 \\)", "\\( v = 2 \\) with no units", "2"]}'::jsonb, '{"answer": 0, "explain": "Name the quantity and give its units — a bare number or a bare variable value can lose the final mark."}'::jsonb),
('additional-maths:2-3-setting-up-and-solving-equations:misc:4baa3013', 'additional-maths', 'additional-maths:2-3-setting-up-and-solving-equations', '2.3 Setting Up and Solving Equations', 'misc', 'mcq', 1, '{"readingTitle": "Misconception check", "reading": "<p><strong>❌ Common misconception:</strong> For a rectangle, \\( x^2 + 2x - 48 = 0 \\) gives \\( x = 6 \\) or \\( x = -8 \\), so the width is \\( -8 \\) cm.</p><p><strong>✅ The correct idea:</strong> A length can never be negative. A weak answer keeps both roots; a strong answer <strong>rejects \\( x = -8 \\)</strong> and states the width is 6 cm, saying why the negative root is impossible.</p>", "question": "Roots \\( 6 \\) and \\( -8 \\) model a width. The width is:", "options": ["6 cm (reject \\( -8 \\))", "\\( -8 \\) cm", "both 6 cm and \\( -8 \\) cm are valid widths", "\\( -2 \\) cm"]}'::jsonb, '{"answer": 0, "explain": "Reject the negative root; the width is 6 cm."}'::jsonb),
('additional-maths:2-3-setting-up-and-solving-equations:misc:7d656bb9', 'additional-maths', 'additional-maths:2-3-setting-up-and-solving-equations', '2.3 Setting Up and Solving Equations', 'misc', 'mcq', 1, '{"readingTitle": "Misconception check", "reading": "<p><strong>❌ Common misconception:</strong> The current speed is found by writing \\( r = 1 \\) and stopping.</p><p><strong>✅ The correct idea:</strong> \"\\( r = 1 \\)\" is a bare number. A weak answer stops there; a strong answer gives a <strong>value with units in context</strong>: ''speed of the current = 1 km/h''. Because \\( r \\) was defined unitless, even ''\\( r = 1 \\) km/h'' is wrong.</p>", "question": "Which is the complete answer for a current speed?", "options": ["speed = 1 km/h", "\\( r = 1 \\)", "\\( r = 1 \\) km/h, the variable with units added", "1"]}'::jsonb, '{"answer": 0, "explain": "Name the quantity and give the units."}'::jsonb),
('additional-maths:2-3-setting-up-and-solving-equations:misc:5de58248', 'additional-maths', 'additional-maths:2-3-setting-up-and-solving-equations', '2.3 Setting Up and Solving Equations', 'misc', 'mcq', 1, '{"readingTitle": "Misconception check", "reading": "<p><strong>❌ Common misconception:</strong> \"5 more than 3 times \\( x \\)\" is written \\( 3(x + 5) \\) or \\( 5(3x) \\).</p><p><strong>✅ The correct idea:</strong> Translate step by step: ''3 times \\( x \\)'' is \\( 3x \\), then ''5 more than'' adds 5 to <em>that</em>: \\( 3x + 5 \\). A weak answer brackets or multiplies wrongly; a strong answer builds the expression in order.</p>", "question": "\"5 more than 3 times \\( x \\)\" is:", "options": ["\\( 3x + 5 \\)", "\\( 3(x + 5) \\)", "\\( 5(3x) \\)", "\\( 3x - 5 \\)"]}'::jsonb, '{"answer": 0, "explain": "\\( 3x \\) first, then add 5: \\( 3x + 5 \\)."}'::jsonb),
('additional-maths:2-3-setting-up-and-solving-equations:misc:8f0ff265', 'additional-maths', 'additional-maths:2-3-setting-up-and-solving-equations', '2.3 Setting Up and Solving Equations', 'misc', 'mcq', 1, '{"readingTitle": "Misconception check", "reading": "<p><strong>❌ Common misconception:</strong> For simultaneous \\( y = x + 1 \\) and \\( x^2 + y^2 = 25 \\), the student finds \\( x = 3 \\) and \\( x = -4 \\) and stops.</p><p><strong>✅ The correct idea:</strong> Simultaneous solutions come in <strong>pairs</strong>. A weak answer gives only the \\( x \\)-values; a strong answer back-substitutes into \\( y = x + 1 \\) to give \\( (3,\\ 4) \\) and \\( (-4,\\ -3) \\).</p>", "question": "With \\( x = 3 \\) and \\( y = x + 1 \\), the point is:", "options": ["\\( (3,\\ 4) \\)", "\\( (3,\\ 3) \\)", "\\( (4,\\ 3) \\)", "\\( (3,\\ 0) \\)"]}'::jsonb, '{"answer": 0, "explain": "\\( y = 3 + 1 = 4 \\), so the pair is \\( (3,\\ 4) \\)."}'::jsonb),
('additional-maths:2-3-setting-up-and-solving-equations:misc:6d6eaa45', 'additional-maths', 'additional-maths:2-3-setting-up-and-solving-equations', '2.3 Setting Up and Solving Equations', 'misc', 'mcq', 1, '{"readingTitle": "Misconception check", "reading": "<p><strong>❌ Common misconception:</strong> \"Show that the equation simplifies to \\( r^2 + 15r - 16 = 0 \\)\" is answered by solving it to get \\( r = 1 \\).</p><p><strong>✅ The correct idea:</strong> A ''show that'' asks you to <strong>reach the printed result</strong>, not to solve it. A weak answer jumps to the roots; a strong answer clears the fractions and rearranges line by line until \\( r^2 + 15r - 16 = 0 \\) appears.</p>", "question": "A ''show that'' question wants you to:", "options": ["Derive the given result step by step", "Solve for the unknown and give its numerical value", "Give a decimal answer", "Draw the graph"]}'::jsonb, '{"answer": 0, "explain": "The result is given; you must show the working that leads to it."}'::jsonb),
('additional-maths:2-3-setting-up-and-solving-equations:tips:ab6f0a37', 'additional-maths', 'additional-maths:2-3-setting-up-and-solving-equations', '2.3 Setting Up and Solving Equations', 'tips', 'mcq', 1, '{"readingTitle": "explain — The modelling routine (0 → full marks)", "reading": "<p><strong>0 marks:</strong> jumping straight to numbers with no defined variable and no units.</p><p><strong>Partial:</strong> a correct equation solved to a bare number, e.g. \"\\( x = 6 \\)\", with no context.</p><p><strong>Full marks:</strong> \"Let \\( x \\) be the width in cm\" → \\( x(x+2) = 48 \\) → \\( x = 6 \\) (reject \\( -8 \\)) → \"the width is 6 cm, the length 8 cm\". Define, translate, solve, interpret.</p>", "question": "What lifts a partial answer to full marks in a modelling question?", "options": ["Defining the variable and interpreting in context", "Working faster", "Giving the answer to more decimal places for accuracy", "Using a graph"]}'::jsonb, '{"answer": 0, "explain": "The interpretation and definition steps carry marks beyond just solving."}'::jsonb),
('additional-maths:2-3-setting-up-and-solving-equations:tips:d3a3439c', 'additional-maths', 'additional-maths:2-3-setting-up-and-solving-equations', '2.3 Setting Up and Solving Equations', 'tips', 'mcq', 1, '{"readingTitle": "tip — Reject the impossible root", "reading": "<p>Every quadratic or cubic from a context can throw up a root that cannot happen — a negative length, a negative speed, a fractional person. Write the rejected root down and say <strong>why</strong>: \"reject \\( x = -8 \\) as a width cannot be negative.\" Silently dropping it can still lose the reasoning mark.</p>", "question": "When you reject a root you should:", "options": ["State which root and why it is impossible", "Erase it with no comment", "Keep both roots and let the examiner pick the right one", "Round it to zero"]}'::jsonb, '{"answer": 0, "explain": "Examiners credit the explicit rejection with a reason."}'::jsonb),
('additional-maths:2-3-setting-up-and-solving-equations:tips:0569f100', 'additional-maths', 'additional-maths:2-3-setting-up-and-solving-equations', '2.3 Setting Up and Solving Equations', 'tips', 'mcq', 1, '{"readingTitle": "explain — Answer with a value AND units", "reading": "<p>The final mark in a modelling question is often for the <strong>form of the answer</strong>. In 2023''s boat question, \"\\( r = 1 \\)\" and even \"\\( r = 1 \\) km/h\" were marked wrong because \\( r \\) was a unitless variable — the answer needed was \"the speed of the current is 1 km/h\". Always name the quantity the question asked for and attach its units.</p>", "question": "Why did \"\\( r = 1 \\)\" lose the final mark in the 2023 boat question?", "options": ["It gave a bare value, not the speed with units in context", "The arithmetic must have gone wrong somewhere in the working", "\\( r = 1 \\) is not a root", "It used the wrong formula"]}'::jsonb, '{"answer": 0, "explain": "The question asked for the speed of the current, which must be stated as a value with units."}'::jsonb),
('additional-maths:2-3-setting-up-and-solving-equations:fib:89be61e9', 'additional-maths', 'additional-maths:2-3-setting-up-and-solving-equations', '2.3 Setting Up and Solving Equations', 'fib', 'fib', 1, '{"question": "The first step in modelling a worded problem is to define the ___B1___ and state what it represents.", "blankOptions": {"B1": ["reject", "1", "unknown", "plus"]}}'::jsonb, '{"blanks": {"B1": "unknown"}}'::jsonb),
('additional-maths:2-3-setting-up-and-solving-equations:fib:aa67ccca', 'additional-maths', 'additional-maths:2-3-setting-up-and-solving-equations', '2.3 Setting Up and Solving Equations', 'fib', 'fib', 1, '{"question": "When a quadratic equation for a length gives a negative root, you must ___B1___ it, because a length cannot be negative.", "blankOptions": {"B1": ["plus", "substitution", "minus", "reject"]}}'::jsonb, '{"blanks": {"B1": "reject"}}'::jsonb),
('additional-maths:2-3-setting-up-and-solving-equations:fib:b1be64f4', 'additional-maths', 'additional-maths:2-3-setting-up-and-solving-equations', '2.3 Setting Up and Solving Equations', 'fib', 'fib', 1, '{"question": "To solve one linear and one quadratic equation together, use the method of ___B1___.", "blankOptions": {"B1": ["units", "minus", "16", "substitution"]}}'::jsonb, '{"blanks": {"B1": "substitution"}}'::jsonb),
('additional-maths:2-3-setting-up-and-solving-equations:fib:a3338372', 'additional-maths', 'additional-maths:2-3-setting-up-and-solving-equations', '2.3 Setting Up and Solving Equations', 'fib', 'fib', 1, '{"question": "In the boat problem the two roots were 1 and \\( -16 \\); the current speed must be positive, so the answer is ___B1___ km/h.", "blankOptions": {"B1": ["unknown", "units", "1", "minus"]}}'::jsonb, '{"blanks": {"B1": "1"}}'::jsonb),
