('additional-maths:2-4-sequences-and-recurrence-relationships:mcq:d1cf9bea', 'additional-maths', 'additional-maths:2-4-sequences-and-recurrence-relationships', '2.4 Sequences and Recurrence Relationships', 'mcq', 'mcq', 1, '{"question": "£400 grows at \\( 5\\% \\) per year: \\( x_{n+1} = 1.05x_n \\) with \\( x_1 = 400 \\). Find \\( x_3 \\).", "options": ["\\( £441.00 \\)", "\\( £420.00 \\)", "\\( £463.05 \\)", "\\( £440.00 \\)"]}'::jsonb, '{"answer": 0, "explain": "\\( x_2 = 1.05 \\times 400 = 420 \\), then \\( x_3 = 1.05 \\times 420 = 441 \\). (\\( 420 \\) is \\( x_2 \\); \\( 463.05 \\) is \\( x_4 \\).)"}'::jsonb),
('additional-maths:2-4-sequences-and-recurrence-relationships:mcq:e114d125', 'additional-maths', 'additional-maths:2-4-sequences-and-recurrence-relationships', '2.4 Sequences and Recurrence Relationships', 'mcq', 'mcq', 1, '{"question": "For \\( x_{n+2} = x_{n+1} + 2x_n \\) with \\( x_1 = 2 \\) and \\( x_2 = 1 \\), find \\( x_4 \\).", "options": ["\\( 7 \\)", "\\( 5 \\)", "\\( 3 \\)", "\\( 11 \\)"]}'::jsonb, '{"answer": 0, "explain": "\\( x_3 = x_2 + 2x_1 = 1 + 4 = 5 \\), then \\( x_4 = x_3 + 2x_2 = 5 + 2 = 7 \\)."}'::jsonb),
('additional-maths:2-4-sequences-and-recurrence-relationships:tf:aa679884', 'additional-maths', 'additional-maths:2-4-sequences-and-recurrence-relationships', '2.4 Sequences and Recurrence Relationships', 'tf', 'tf', 1, '{"question": "A recurrence relationship needs at least one starting value to generate the sequence."}'::jsonb, '{"answer": true, "explain": "The rule only tells you how to get from known terms to the next, so you must be given a first term (or two, for a second-order rule) to begin."}'::jsonb),
('additional-maths:2-4-sequences-and-recurrence-relationships:tf:7235f084', 'additional-maths', 'additional-maths:2-4-sequences-and-recurrence-relationships', '2.4 Sequences and Recurrence Relationships', 'tf', 'tf', 1, '{"question": "\\( x_{n+1} = x_n + a \\) describes a sequence that changes by a fixed amount each term."}'::jsonb, '{"answer": true, "explain": "Adding the same \\( a \\) every step gives a constant common difference — an arithmetic sequence."}'::jsonb),
('additional-maths:2-4-sequences-and-recurrence-relationships:tf:7fd40706', 'additional-maths', 'additional-maths:2-4-sequences-and-recurrence-relationships', '2.4 Sequences and Recurrence Relationships', 'tf', 'tf', 1, '{"question": "\\( x_{n+1} = a x_n \\) and \\( x_{n+1} = x_n + a \\) generate the same sequence."}'::jsonb, '{"answer": false, "explain": "The first multiplies by \\( a \\) (geometric), the second adds \\( a \\) (arithmetic) — quite different sequences."}'::jsonb),
('additional-maths:2-4-sequences-and-recurrence-relationships:tf:d1cc6cfb', 'additional-maths', 'additional-maths:2-4-sequences-and-recurrence-relationships', '2.4 Sequences and Recurrence Relationships', 'tf', 'tf', 1, '{"question": "A second-order recurrence such as \\( x_{n+2} = x_{n+1} + x_n \\) can be started from a single value."}'::jsonb, '{"answer": false, "explain": "It uses the two previous terms, so it needs two starting values."}'::jsonb),
('additional-maths:2-4-sequences-and-recurrence-relationships:tf:f14780f2', 'additional-maths', 'additional-maths:2-4-sequences-and-recurrence-relationships', '2.4 Sequences and Recurrence Relationships', 'tf', 'tf', 1, '{"question": "£1000 at 3% compound interest per year is modelled by \\( x_{n+1} = 1.03 x_n \\)."}'::jsonb, '{"answer": true, "explain": "Growth of 3% multiplies the balance by \\( 1 + 0.03 = 1.03 \\) each year."}'::jsonb),
('additional-maths:2-4-sequences-and-recurrence-relationships:tf:12ccdf24', 'additional-maths', 'additional-maths:2-4-sequences-and-recurrence-relationships', '2.4 Sequences and Recurrence Relationships', 'tf', 'tf', 1, '{"question": "In the sequence \\( 5,\\ 8,\\ 11,\\ 14,\\ \\dots \\) the recurrence is \\( x_{n+1} = x_n + 3 \\)."}'::jsonb, '{"answer": true, "explain": "The constant difference is \\( +3 \\), so each term is the previous term plus 3 (with \\( x_1 = 5 \\))."}'::jsonb),
('additional-maths:2-4-sequences-and-recurrence-relationships:tf:84076733', 'additional-maths', 'additional-maths:2-4-sequences-and-recurrence-relationships', '2.4 Sequences and Recurrence Relationships', 'tf', 'tf', 1, '{"question": "For \\( x_{n+1} = 2x_n \\) with \\( x_1 = 3 \\), the term \\( x_3 \\) equals 12."}'::jsonb, '{"answer": true, "explain": "\\( x_2 = 6 \\) and \\( x_3 = 2 \\times 6 = 12 \\)."}'::jsonb),
('additional-maths:2-4-sequences-and-recurrence-relationships:tf:096d46ea', 'additional-maths', 'additional-maths:2-4-sequences-and-recurrence-relationships', '2.4 Sequences and Recurrence Relationships', 'tf', 'tf', 1, '{"question": "An asset that depreciates by 15% each year is modelled by \\( x_{n+1} = 1.15 x_n \\)."}'::jsonb, '{"answer": false, "explain": "Depreciation of 15% leaves 85%, so the multiplier is \\( 0.85 \\), not \\( 1.15 \\)."}'::jsonb),
('additional-maths:2-4-sequences-and-recurrence-relationships:learn:924843e4', 'additional-maths', 'additional-maths:2-4-sequences-and-recurrence-relationships', '2.4 Sequences and Recurrence Relationships', 'learn', 'mcq', 1, '{"readingTitle": "What is a recurrence relationship?", "reading": "<p>A <strong>recurrence relationship</strong> (or recurrence relation) is a rule that gives each term of a sequence from one or more <em>earlier</em> terms. It is a <strong>term-to-term</strong> rule, not a position-to-term formula.</p>\n            <ul>\n              <li>The <strong>subscript</strong> tells you the position: \\( x_n \\) is the \\( n\\)th term, \\( x_{n+1} \\) is the term straight after it, and \\( x_{n+2} \\) is the one after that.</li>\n              <li>A rule such as \\( x_{n+1} = x_n + 3 \\) reads \"the next term equals this term plus 3\".</li>\n              <li>You cannot generate the sequence from the rule alone — you also need a <strong>starting value</strong> (the first term). A rule that reaches back two terms, like \\( x_{n+2} = x_{n+1} + x_n \\), needs <strong>two</strong> starting values.</li>\n              <li>The phrase \"<em>for all positive integers \\( n \\)</em>\" simply means the rule applies right from the start of the sequence.</li>\n            </ul>", "question": "In \\( x_{n+1} = x_n + 5 \\), what does \\( x_{n+1} \\) represent?", "options": ["The term immediately after \\( x_n \\)", "The term immediately before \\( x_n \\)", "\\( 5 \\) times \\( x_n \\)", "The starting value of the sequence"]}'::jsonb, '{"answer": 0, "explain": "The subscript \\( n+1 \\) is one position further on than \\( n \\), so \\( x_{n+1} \\) is the next term after \\( x_n \\)."}'::jsonb),
('additional-maths:2-4-sequences-and-recurrence-relationships:learn:ce08e9fe', 'additional-maths', 'additional-maths:2-4-sequences-and-recurrence-relationships', '2.4 Sequences and Recurrence Relationships', 'learn', 'mcq', 1, '{"readingTitle": "How do you generate an arithmetic (linear) sequence?", "reading": "<p>A first-order recurrence of the form \\( x_{n+1} = x_n + a \\) <strong>adds</strong> the same fixed amount \\( a \\) to get each new term. This produces an <strong>arithmetic</strong> sequence — a constant step up (or, if \\( a \\) is negative, down).</p>\n            <p><strong>Worked example — generate the first four terms of \\( x_{n+1} = x_n + 4 \\) with \\( x_1 = 3 \\):</strong></p>\n            <table class=\"worked\">\n              <tr><td>1. Start: \\( x_1 = 3 \\).</td></tr>\n              <tr><td>2. \\( x_2 = x_1 + 4 = 3 + 4 = 7 \\).</td></tr>\n              <tr><td>3. \\( x_3 = x_2 + 4 = 7 + 4 = 11 \\).</td></tr>\n              <tr><td>4. \\( x_4 = x_3 + 4 = 11 + 4 = 15 \\).</td></tr>\n            </table>\n            <p>So the sequence begins \\( 3,\\ 7,\\ 11,\\ 15,\\ \\dots \\) — a fixed step of \\( +4 \\), the <strong>common difference</strong>.</p>", "question": "For \\( x_{n+1} = x_n + 6 \\) with \\( x_1 = 5 \\), find \\( x_3 \\).", "options": ["\\( 17 \\)", "\\( 11 \\)", "\\( 23 \\)", "\\( 30 \\)"]}'::jsonb, '{"answer": 0, "explain": "\\( x_2 = 5 + 6 = 11 \\), then \\( x_3 = 11 + 6 = 17 \\). (\\( 11 \\) is only \\( x_2 \\); \\( 23 \\) is \\( x_4 \\).)"}'::jsonb),
('additional-maths:2-4-sequences-and-recurrence-relationships:learn:702a8830', 'additional-maths', 'additional-maths:2-4-sequences-and-recurrence-relationships', '2.4 Sequences and Recurrence Relationships', 'learn', 'mcq', 1, '{"readingTitle": "How do you generate a geometric sequence?", "reading": "<p>A first-order recurrence of the form \\( x_{n+1} = a\\,x_n \\) <strong>multiplies</strong> by the same fixed factor \\( a \\) each time. This produces a <strong>geometric</strong> sequence, with a constant <strong>common ratio</strong> \\( a \\).</p>\n            <p><strong>Watch the difference:</strong> \\( x_{n+1} = x_n + a \\) <em>adds</em> \\( a \\); \\( x_{n+1} = a\\,x_n \\) <em>multiplies</em> by \\( a \\). Mixing these up is the most common slip in this topic.</p>\n            <p><strong>Worked example — generate the first four terms of \\( x_{n+1} = 3x_n \\) with \\( x_1 = 2 \\):</strong></p>\n            <table class=\"worked\">\n              <tr><td>1. Start: \\( x_1 = 2 \\).</td></tr>\n              <tr><td>2. \\( x_2 = 3 \\times 2 = 6 \\).</td></tr>\n              <tr><td>3. \\( x_3 = 3 \\times 6 = 18 \\).</td></tr>\n              <tr><td>4. \\( x_4 = 3 \\times 18 = 54 \\).</td></tr>\n            </table>\n            <p>So the sequence is \\( 2,\\ 6,\\ 18,\\ 54,\\ \\dots \\) — each term \\( 3 \\) times the last.</p>", "question": "For \\( x_{n+1} = 2x_n \\) with \\( x_1 = 5 \\), find \\( x_4 \\).", "options": ["\\( 40 \\)", "\\( 20 \\)", "\\( 80 \\)", "\\( 11 \\)"]}'::jsonb, '{"answer": 0, "explain": "\\( x_2 = 10,\\ x_3 = 20,\\ x_4 = 40 \\). (\\( 20 \\) is \\( x_3 \\); \\( 11 \\) comes from adding instead of multiplying.)"}'::jsonb),
('additional-maths:2-4-sequences-and-recurrence-relationships:learn:88b4bf55', 'additional-maths', 'additional-maths:2-4-sequences-and-recurrence-relationships', '2.4 Sequences and Recurrence Relationships', 'learn', 'mcq', 1, '{"readingTitle": "How do you work with a second-order recurrence?", "reading": "<p>A <strong>second-order</strong> recurrence uses the <strong>two</strong> previous terms, so it needs <strong>two</strong> starting values. The most famous example is the <strong>Fibonacci-style</strong> rule \\( x_{n+2} = x_{n+1} + x_n \\): each term is the sum of the two before it.</p>\n            <p><strong>Worked example — generate the first five terms of \\( x_{n+2} = x_{n+1} + x_n \\) with \\( x_1 = 2 \\) and \\( x_2 = 3 \\):</strong></p>\n            <table class=\"worked\">\n              <tr><td>1. Given: \\( x_1 = 2,\\ x_2 = 3 \\).</td></tr>\n              <tr><td>2. \\( x_3 = x_2 + x_1 = 3 + 2 = 5 \\).</td></tr>\n              <tr><td>3. \\( x_4 = x_3 + x_2 = 5 + 3 = 8 \\).</td></tr>\n              <tr><td>4. \\( x_5 = x_4 + x_3 = 8 + 5 = 13 \\).</td></tr>\n            </table>\n            <p>So the first five terms are \\( 2,\\ 3,\\ 5,\\ 8,\\ 13 \\). Write each line out: examiners reward every correct term, and a single arithmetic slip then costs only one mark.</p>", "question": "For \\( x_{n+2} = x_{n+1} + x_n \\) with \\( x_1 = 1 \\) and \\( x_2 = 4 \\), find \\( x_4 \\).", "options": ["\\( 9 \\)", "\\( 5 \\)", "\\( 14 \\)", "\\( 8 \\)"]}'::jsonb, '{"answer": 0, "explain": "\\( x_3 = 4 + 1 = 5 \\), then \\( x_4 = x_3 + x_2 = 5 + 4 = 9 \\)."}'::jsonb),
('additional-maths:2-4-sequences-and-recurrence-relationships:learn:450748eb', 'additional-maths', 'additional-maths:2-4-sequences-and-recurrence-relationships', '2.4 Sequences and Recurrence Relationships', 'learn', 'mcq', 1, '{"readingTitle": "How do you describe a sequence by a recurrence?", "reading": "<p>Sometimes you are given a sequence and asked for the recurrence that <strong>describes</strong> it. Look for the pattern, then state the rule <em>and</em> the starting value(s).</p>\n            <ul>\n              <li><strong>Constant difference</strong> between terms → \\( x_{n+1} = x_n + d \\) (arithmetic).</li>\n              <li><strong>Constant ratio</strong> between terms → \\( x_{n+1} = r\\,x_n \\) (geometric).</li>\n              <li>Each term the <strong>sum of the two before</strong> → \\( x_{n+2} = x_{n+1} + x_n \\).</li>\n            </ul>\n            <p><strong>Worked example — describe \\( 5,\\ 8,\\ 11,\\ 14,\\ \\dots \\):</strong> the difference is a constant \\( +3 \\), so \\( x_{n+1} = x_n + 3 \\) with \\( x_1 = 5 \\). A rule without its starting value does not fully define the sequence, so always give both.</p>", "question": "Which recurrence describes the sequence \\( 4,\\ 12,\\ 36,\\ 108,\\ \\dots \\)?", "options": ["\\( x_{n+1} = 3x_n,\\ x_1 = 4 \\)", "\\( x_{n+1} = x_n + 8,\\ x_1 = 4 \\)", "\\( x_{n+1} = x_n + 3 \\)", "\\( x_{n+2} = x_{n+1} + x_n \\)"]}'::jsonb, '{"answer": 0, "explain": "Each term is \\( 3 \\) times the last (\\( 12 = 3 \\times 4 \\), \\( 36 = 3 \\times 12 \\)), so it is geometric with ratio \\( 3 \\) and \\( x_1 = 4 \\)."}'::jsonb)
